<h1>@HI{{o ~ suru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <strong>@HI{{o}}</strong>@Vmasustem{{}} @HI{{<strong>suru</strong>}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

With this phrase the speaker is showing politeness towards someone when describing their own actions or state.
<p></p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha @KJ{{before^life}} no @KT{{su-tsuke-su}}wo <strong>o</strong>@KJ{{hold}}chi <strong>shimashita</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I carried the teacher's suitcase.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

This construction cannot be used with all verbs: some verbs express the humble form in irregular ways.
<p></p>

This form is used only to when the speaker's actions or those of his in-group affect someone to whom the speaker wishes to show politeness. 
<p></p>

Verbs of the form @N{{}}@HI{{suru}} form the honorific as @HI{{go}}@N{{}}@HI{{suru}} or, even more politely, @HI{{go}}@N{{}}@HI{{itasu}}. There are a few exceptions that take @HI{{o}} rather than @HI{{go}}.
<p></p>

These verbs with an irregular humble form <em>can</em> be used even if the action does not affect someone to whom the speaker wishes to show politeness.
<p></p>

